  "text": "The robustness of the mapping procedure ensures that only meaningful clusters of branches are tested. This represents an advantage over the arbitrary starting point used by [CITATION_1] and the complex and difficult to optimize starting point used by [CITATION_2] . Our procedure also prevents issues of overparametrization as it starts from models with small numbers of clusters. Counts of substitutions obtained for each branch are then used to partition branches in increasing numbers of subsets. From the resulting clustering tree, we design and fit a series of nested nonhomogeneous models, starting from the most simple one and progressively increasing the number of parameters, until it seems certain that improvement in AIC or BIC score can no longer be achieved. This procedure has the advantage that less than n optimizations are required (45 or 49 optimizations for the rRNA data set, containing 181 branches) and, perhaps more importantly, the models with the largest numbers of clusters, overparameterized and most costly to optimize, are often never optimized as the algorithm settles on models with small numbers of clusters (for instance, two to five dN/dS clusters in the tree of Mantellid frogs, which contains 31 branches). This is in sharp contrast to [CITATION_3] 's approach where all the most parameter-rich models are necessarily optimized.",
